5|$|Miyazaki co-founded Studio <b>Ghibli</b> in 1985. He {{directed}} several {{films with}} <b>Ghibli,</b> including Castle in the Sky in 1986, My Neighbor Totoro in 1988, Kiki's Delivery Service in 1989, and Porco Rosso in 1992. The films {{were met with}} commercial and critical success in Japan. Miyazaki's film Princess Mononoke was the first animated film to win the Japan Academy Prize for Picture of the Year, and briefly became the highest-grossing film in Japan following its release in 1997; its distribution to the Western world greatly increased Ghibli's popularity and influence outside Japan. His 2001 film Spirited Away became the highest-grossing film in Japanese history, winning the Academy Award for Best Animated Feature at the 75th Academy Awards and considered among the greatest animation films of all time. Miyazaki's later films—Howl's Moving Castle, Ponyo, and The Wind Rises—also enjoyed critical and commercial success. Following the release of The Wind Rises, Miyazaki announced his retirement from feature films, however he returned {{to work on a}} new feature film in 2016.|$|E
5|$|Ni no Kuni II: Revenant Kingdom was {{announced}} at PlayStation Experience on December 5, 2015. It {{will be released}} for the PlayStation 4 and Microsoft Windows on January 19, 2018. Studio <b>Ghibli</b> will not have direct involvement with the game. Hino said that the game would better fulfill the ambitions of the original game, with deeper stories and improved visuals.|$|E
5|$|The {{studio is}} praised {{primarily}} for its original and innovative productions, {{and it has}} gretely affected the animated film history over the last decades. Disney studios take inspiration {{from some of the}} other studios such as Studio <b>Ghibli</b> and Madhouse because the production team feels that many of the Japan's studios are ahead of them and capable of making better animation, which is the reason why they get inspiration from what those studios produce.|$|E
